{"cursor":"1357","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n\n\n'Bar' is a form of folk dance of Eastern Turkey. The word bar is said to come\nfrom the Armenian word \"ÕÕ¡Ö\" (bar) which means dance in that language. With\ntheir structure and formation, they are the dances performed by groups in the\nopen. They are spread, in general, all over the region of Eastern Anatolia,\nespecially in Erzurum, Artvin, Bayburt, AÄrÄ±, Kars, and Erzincan provinces. The\ncharacteristic of their formation is that they are performed side-by-side, hand,\nshoulder and arm-in-arm. Woman and man bars are different from one another. The\nprincipal instruments of bar dances are davul and zurna (shrill pipe). The\ndominant measures in bars are 5/8 and 9/8. Occasionally measures of 6/8 and 12/8\nare also used. Aksak 9/8 measures which are the most characteristic measures, in\nparticular, of the Turkish folk music are applied with extremely different and\ninteresting structures in this dance.\n","linknr":299,"url":"Bar_(dance)","recorded":1362565062,"links":32,"instances":[],"pdf":[],"categories":["Turkish dances"],"headings":["External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b8/Verbreitungskarte_der_t%C3%BCrkischen_Volkst%C3%A4nze.png/300px-Verbreitungskarte_der_t%C3%BCrkischen_Volkst%C3%A4nze.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/36/Flag_of_Albania.svg/22px-Flag_of_Albania.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bf/Flag_of_Bosnia_and_Herzegovina.svg/22px-Flag_of_Bosnia_and_Herzegovina.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9a/Flag_of_Bulgaria.svg/22px-Flag_of_Bulgaria.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1b/Flag_of_Croatia.svg/22px-Flag_of_Croatia.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/comm